# Project Commands Reference

This file explains the common commands used in this Playwright automation project.
Each command includes what it does, why it is useful, and when to use it.

---

## Install TypeScript

```powershell
npm install --save-dev typescript
```

Alternative short form:

```powershell
npm install -D typescript
```

What:
Installs TypeScript as a development dependency and adds it under `devDependencies` in `package.json`.

Why:
TypeScript lets you write `.ts` files and compile them to JavaScript. It also gives better type checking and editor suggestions.

When:
Use this once when you want to start writing or compiling TypeScript files in the project.

Note:
After installing locally, run the TypeScript compiler with:

```powershell
npx tsc demo1.ts
```

---

## Check Node.js Version

```powershell
node -v
```

What:
Prints the installed Node.js version.

Why:
Playwright, npm packages, and TypeScript require Node.js. Checking the version helps confirm your environment is ready.

When:
Use this before setup, after installing Node.js, or when troubleshooting npm/playwright command issues.

---

## Initialize a Playwright Project

```powershell
npm init playwright
```

What:
Starts Playwright's project setup wizard.

Why:
It creates the basic Playwright project structure, config file, sample tests, and installs required packages.

When:
Use this only when creating a new Playwright project from scratch. Do not run it repeatedly in an existing configured project unless you intentionally want to regenerate setup files.

---

## Install Playwright Browsers

```powershell
npx playwright install
```

What:
Downloads browser binaries used by Playwright, such as Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit.

Why:
Playwright needs its managed browsers to run tests consistently.

When:
Use this after installing Playwright dependencies, after cloning the repo on a new machine, or when Playwright says browser executables are missing.

---

## Run All Playwright Tests

```powershell
npx playwright test
```

What:
Runs all test files found under the configured test directory.

Why:
This verifies the full automation suite.

When:
Use this before committing code, after major changes, or when you want a full regression run.

---

## Run One Test File in Debug Mode

```powershell
npx playwright test tests/clientAppPO.spec.js --debug
```

What:
Runs only `tests/clientAppPO.spec.js` in Playwright debug mode.

Why:
Debug mode opens the browser headed, slows execution, and lets you inspect locators and steps.

When:
Use this when a specific test is failing or when you want to understand each browser action step by step.

---

## Run the Data-Driven Client App Test

```powershell
npx playwright test tests/TestdataClientApp.spec.js
```

What:
Runs only the `TestdataClientApp.spec.js` test file.

Why:
This file uses test data from JSON/custom fixtures to run client app scenarios.

When:
Use this when working on data-driven tests, fixture logic, or the client app Page Object Model flow.

---

## Run Tests by Tag or Text

```powershell
npx playwright test --grep "@web"
```

What:
Runs only tests whose title matches `@web`.

Why:
Tags let you run a selected group of tests instead of the whole suite.

When:
Use this when you want to run only web UI tests or any tests marked with `@web`.

Important PowerShell note:
Always put `@web` in quotes in PowerShell. Without quotes, PowerShell may parse `@web` incorrectly.

Also, grep is case-sensitive. If the test title uses `@Web`, run:

```powershell
npx playwright test --grep "@Web"
```

---

## Run a Test with a Specific Playwright Config

```powershell
npx playwright test tests/OtherRahulsheetyAcademy.spec.js --config playwright.config1.js
```

What:
Runs `OtherRahulsheetyAcademy.spec.js` using `playwright.config1.js` instead of the default `playwright.config.js`.

Why:
Different config files can define different browsers, projects, retries, workers, screenshots, trace settings, and permissions.

When:
Use this when you want to test with the alternate project configuration.

---

## Run a Test with a Specific Config and Browser Project

```powershell
npx playwright test tests/moreValidations.spec.js --config playwright.config1.js --project=chrome
```

What:
Runs `moreValidations.spec.js` using `playwright.config1.js` and only the `chrome` project defined inside that config.

Why:
When a config has multiple projects, such as `chrome` and `safari`, `--project` lets you choose one.

When:
Use this when you want to run a test only in one configured browser/project.

